The pizza here is so very good! They keep it interesting by changing the menu at times and also offering unusual daily specials. While it might seem a lot to drop $18 for a large pizza it really is SPECIALITY pizza with top-notch ingredients. I love the thin crust variety, as well as their use of balsamic and less ordinary cheeses. There are always at least two vegetarian options, although I would love more. I gave it a four rather than five star rating because of the physical environment: concrete floors, somewhat dirty bathroom, cold air near the front door (though the new curtain shielding the entry a bit does help). Yes, I will continue eating at Iggies when downtown for the theatre, etc. I recommend it!

Would give 0 stars if I could, but I can't. I'd been going to this place for a couple of years, paying their overinflated prices as of late, but never again.Because I prefer not to keel over and die as the result of food poisoning. Went into this place for a late lunch and ordered Antipasti and a pie. The bread that comes with the Antipasti was covered in mold (typical Baltimore, I know). Even bread in a convenience store doesn't have mold on it (unless, I guess, you're in Baltimore). What's ironic is that in the two years or so years I've frequented Iggies, the Antipasti never even came with bread. The cheeses, meats, and vegetables from before were changed to some crap out of a Sun of Italy jar and thrown on a plate with a wedge of bread in the middle. An obvious cost-cutting technique even though the price of damn near everything on the menu has gone up. I mean, seriously, I understand how inflation works, raise the prices but keep the quality and standards. Now, I know what you're thinking: "Maybe this was a one-off occurrence, it won't be like that when I go." Proceed at your own peril, as this place has been on a slippery slope as of late. I'm not sure if they've had a change in management or ownership, but this place is Ramsay's Kitchen Nightmares bound. Not only are their tactics bad business, but they're gonna get someone sick, if they haven't already. The Baltimore Sun and City Paper may keep propping them up with those ridiculous 'best pizza tournaments', but on a day to day basis, this place is doomed to fail unless something changes quick. You can tell by the Google ratings. Prior to a year or so ago, I'd be shocked to see Iggies with anything less than four stars. Now it's a regular occurrence. Hell, after the last two visits, I'm surprised they're still open.

The food was good, if not a bit expensive for cafeteria style service. You are expected to clean your own table, complete with putting glasses and silverware in organized bins. If you are a restaurant snob then this place is probably not for you. They also don't serve alcohol and have few non-alcoholic drink selections. However it is BYOB, which is always a plus if you don't mind it. Service was okay. Not completely rude like some say they are, but they weren't notably friendly either. Regardless, the food was delivered rather quickly after ordering, which was nice.
